### Exclude modules from autolinking in package.json

Source: https://github.com/expo/expo/blob/main/docs/pages/bare/installing-expo-modules.mdx

Use the expo.autolinking.exclude property to prevent specific native modules from being linked into your project.

```json
{
  "name": "...",
  "dependencies": {},
  "expo": {
    "autolinking": {
      "exclude": ["expo-keep-awake"]
    }
  }
}
```

### Expo Router notation > Types of route notation > Square brackets

Source: https://github.com/expo/expo/blob/main/docs/pages/router/basics/notation.mdx

If you see square brackets in a file or directory name, you are looking at a _dynamic route_. The name of the route includes a parameter that can be used when rendering the page. The parameter could be either in a directory name or a file name. For example, a file named **[userName].tsx** will match `/evanbacon`, `/expo`, or another username. Then, you can access that parameter with the `useLocalSearchParams` hook inside the page, using that to load the data for that specific user.

--------------------------------

### Expo Router notation

Source: https://github.com/expo/expo/blob/main/docs/pages/router/basics/notation.mdx

When you look inside the **src/app** directory in a typical Expo Router project, you'll see a lot more than some simple file and directory names. What do the parentheses and brackets mean? Let's learn the significance of file-based routing notation and how it allows you to define complex navigation patterns.

--------------------------------

### Configuration > exclude

Source: https://github.com/expo/expo/blob/main/docs/pages/modules/autolinking.mdx

The exclude option allows developers to specify package names that should be omitted from autolinking. This helps reduce binary size by excluding packages not used by specific platforms. While Expo modules are excluded via configuration files, React Native modules can also be excluded by setting platform configurations to null in a react-native.config.js file.
